A number of points here are wrong. It is not especially helpful to misrepresent a sophisticated protocol like Elves.

Elves uses cryptographically-secure random verifiable sampling together with escalation-by-default. Basically, all nodes execute everything *unless* it can be proven statistically impossible that the work report is incorrect. Because we have a closed system with clear probabilities we can model this accurately, and in practice nodes only need to execute about 1/30th of the total work most of the time. Finality happens only when >2/3 of validators agree that there is no chance of any historical work reports being invalid.

